petition to efficiency in production and consumption within ecosystems. He shows how power—which he defines as the rate at which organisms acquire and apply energy—is tied to the emergence of cooperation, and how the modern economy, which for the first time has established a monopoly over the biosphere by a single species, is a continuation of evolutionary trends stretching back to the dawn of life. Vermeij persuasively argues that we can find solutions to the many problems arising from this extreme concentration of power by broadening our exclusively human-centered perspective.A masterful work by one of today’s most innovative and forward-thinking naturalists, The Evolution of Power offers a new understanding of our place in the grand sweep of evolutionary history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEvolution (Biology)2DLC. 0aEvolution (Biology). 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aA New Understanding of the History of Life.  aGeerat J. Vermeij.  aPrinceton University Press.  aThe Evolution of Power.  abiology.  aecology.  aeconomics.  aecosystems.  aevolution.  aevolutionary biology.  ahistory and evolution of life.  ahistory.  ahuman history.  amonopoly.  apaleoecology.  apaleontology.  apatterns of power.  aphilsophy of biology.  apower.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2023 Englishz978311131921608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2023z9783111318615oZDB-23-DPM08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-